Section 1. Introduction

-   The SCHC specification [RFC8724] describes generic header compression
-   and fragmentation techniques that can be used on all Low-Power Wide
-   Area Network (LPWAN) technologies defined in [RFC8376].  Even though
-   those technologies share a great number of common features like star-
-   oriented topologies, network architecture, devices with
-   communications that are mostly quite predictable, etc., they do have
-   some slight differences with respect to payload sizes, reactiveness,
-   etc.
+   The SCHC specification [RFC8724] describes generic header compression
+   and fragmentation techniques that can be used on all Low-Power Wide
+   Area Network (LPWAN) technologies defined in [RFC8376]. The SCHC
+   Architecture [DRAFT-SCHC-ARCH] defines the logical framework and
+   core components—such as Endpoints, Instances, Sessions, Contexts,
+   and Domains—whereby SCHC processing is deployed and managed.
+   Even though LPWAN technologies share common features like star-oriented
+   topologies, network architecture, and predictable communications,
+   they have slight differences with respect to payload sizes, reactiveness,
+   and framing.

-   SCHC provides a generic framework that enables those devices to
-   communicate on IP networks.  However, for efficient performance, some
-   parameters and modes of operation need to be set appropriately for
-   each of the LPWAN technologies.
+   SCHC provides a generic framework that enables those devices to
+   communicate on IP networks.  However, for efficient performance, some
+   parameters, Instance Configurations, and modes of operation need to
+   be set appropriately for each of the LPWAN technologies.


Section 2. Terminology

    This section defines the terminology and abbreviations used in this
    document.  For all other definitions, please look up the SCHC
-   specification [RFC8724].
+   specification [RFC8724] and the SCHC Architecture [DRAFT-SCHC-ARCH].

+   Context:  A Set of Rules (SoR) together with metadata, shared by two or
+      more Instances, as defined in [DRAFT-SCHC-ARCH].
+
+   Discriminator:  An information element (such as DevEUI or FPort range)
+      used by the Dispatcher to route SCHC Datagrams to the target Instance.
+
+   Dispatcher:  A logical component of the Endpoint that routes incoming
+      packets to the appropriate Instance based on admission rules and
+      Discriminators.
+
+   Domain:  A logical grouping of Instances that share a common set of
+      Contexts for SCHC operations, such as a LoRaWAN network domain.
+
+   Endpoint:  A logical entity that provides SCHC functionality by hosting
+      one or more SCHC Instances.
+
+   Instance:  A logical component of an Endpoint that executes SCHC
+      operations (C/D and F/R) using a specific Context and Instance
+      Configuration.
+
+   Session:  A communication session between two or more Instances that
+      share a common Context within a Domain.
+
+   Set of Rules (SoR):  The collection of C/D, F/R, and no-compression Rules
+      available to an Instance.
+
+   Set of Variables (SoV):  Runtime parameters and session variables (such
+      as fragmentation timers, retransmission counters, and window state)
+      associated with an active Session.


Section 3. SCHC Overview

-   It defines:
-
-   1.  Compression mechanisms to avoid transporting information known by
-       both sender and receiver over the air.  Known information is part
-       of the "context".  This component is called the "SCHC
-       Compression/Decompression" (SCHC C/D).
-
-   2.  Fragmentation mechanisms to allow SCHC Packet transportation on a
-       small, and potentially variable, MTU.  This component is called
-       the "SCHC Fragmentation/Reassembly" (SCHC F/R).
-
-   Context exchange or pre-provisioning is out of scope of this
-   document.
+   It defines:
+
+   1.  Compression mechanisms to avoid transporting information known by
+       both sender and receiver over the air.  Known information is part
+       of the Context (Set of Rules).  This function is called "SCHC
+       Compression/Decompression" (SCHC C/D).
+
+   2.  Fragmentation mechanisms to allow SCHC Packet transportation on a
+       small, and potentially variable, MTU.  This function is called
+       "SCHC Fragmentation/Reassembly" (SCHC F/R).
+
+   Context provisioning, distribution, and domain management are out of
+   scope of this document.

